And so I would say that the lack of a change is exactly what makes the country stable and successful in the long run in terms of economy (and many other fields.)

 

But the perceptions that are made, mostly in the US, about the lack of diversity and failing immigrants are of course ridiculous. The amount of various immigrants we have now is a lot more than it was say 30 years ago. The US has however a totally different policy.

 

Only Sweden has the right to judge so far as they are not a melting pot. Anyone with the right amount of knowledge of Swedish history should assume it as a fact that there is a low percent of immigrants (that feels Swedish) in Sweden. Sure, there are a lot of immigrants, but a great portion of them are still immigrants, even though they have lived in Sweden for decades. That's the difference.

Almost half of the population was 25% Swedish or less in the 2010 Census.
